Task Scheduler — Merge Overlapping Project Intervals

In a project management system, tasks are represented as intervals, where each interval defines the start and end times of a specific task. Sometimes, tasks may overlap with each other, and you need to merge these overlapping tasks into a single task.

You are given an array of tasks, where each task is represented by an interval [start, end], and your task is to merge all overlapping intervals and return a list of non-overlapping intervals.

Input format :
First line contains an integer n — the number of tasks/intervals
Each of the next n lines contains two space-separated integers representing the start and end time of each task interval [start, end]
Output format :
Print each merged interval on a new line in the format:
[start, end] Where start and end represent the merged interval boundaries

Code constraints :
The number of intervals n will be between 1 and 10^4.

The start and end values of each interval are integers between 0 and 10^6.

Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
4
1 3
2 4
6 8
7 9
Output 1 :
[1, 4]
[6, 9]
Input 2 :
3
1 2
3 4
5 6
Output 2 :
[1, 2]
[3, 4]
[5, 6]


#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;

    vector<pair<int,int>> intervals(n);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        int u, v;
        cin >> u >> v;
        intervals[i] = {u, v};
    }

    // Sort by first value
    sort(intervals.begin(), intervals.end());

    vector<vector<int>> res;

    // Push first interval
    res.push_back({intervals[0].first, intervals[0].second});

    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {

        // Overlap
        if (intervals[i].first <= res.back()[1]) {
            res.back()[1] =
                max(res.back()[1], intervals[i].second);
        }
        else {
            res.push_back(
                {intervals[i].first, intervals[i].second}
            );
        }
    }

    // Print
    for (auto it : res) {
        cout << it[0] << " " << it[1] << "\n";
    }

    return 0;
}
